==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: flaccid
<hw>flac"cid</hw> <pr>(fl⟦acr⟧k"s⟦icr⟧d <it>or</it>
fl⟦acr⟧s"s⟦icr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>flaccidus</ets>, fr.
<ets>flaccus</ets> flabby: cf. OF. <ets>flaccide</ets>.]</ety>
<def>Yielding to pressure for want of firmness and stiffness; soft and
weak; limber; lax; drooping; flabby; <as>as, a <ex>flaccid</ex> muscle;
<ex>flaccid</ex> flesh.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Religious profession . . . has become <qex>flacced</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>flac"cid*ly</wf> <pr>(fl⟦acr⟧k"s⟦icr⟧d*l⟦ycr⟧
<it>or</it> fl⟦acr⟧s"s⟦icr⟧d*l⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>flac"cid*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flaccidity</ent>⟦br⟧
